<!-- ========================================================================== -->
<!-- CRITICAL DIAGNOSTIC: Docker MySQL Connectivity Issue (2025-11-19)        -->
<!-- ========================================================================== -->
<div style="background-color: #fff3cd; border: 2px solid #ff9800; padding: var(--spacing-medium); margin: var(--spacing-medium) 0; border-radius: 4px;">
    <h3 style="color: #d84315; font-family: var(--header-font); margin-top: 0;">🔴 CRITICAL: Docker Containers Cannot Connect to Production MySQL</h3>
    
    <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Current Situation (Nov 19, 2025)</h4>
    <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); line-height: 1.6;">
        <li><strong>Port 3001</strong>: ✅ <strong>WORKING</strong> - Returns HTML content (native Perl process running locally on host)</li>
        <li><strong>Port 3000</strong>: ✅ <strong>RETURNS CONTENT</strong> - Docker dev container responds with HTTP 200 (but cannot access production MySQL)</li>
        <li><strong>Port 5000</strong>: ✅ <strong>RETURNS CONTENT</strong> - Docker prod container responds with HTTP 200 (but cannot access production MySQL)</li>
        <li><strong>Production MySQL</strong>: ❌ <strong>UNREACHABLE FROM DOCKER</strong> - Error 2002 (Connection refused on port 115) when containers attempt to reach 192.168.1.198</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Root Cause Analysis</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #f5f5f5; padding: var(--spacing-medium); border-left: 4px solid #ff9800; margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
        <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>Issue</strong>: Docker containers are isolated on their own internal network (172.20.0.0/16) and cannot route packets to the host network (192.168.0.0/16).</p>
        
        <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>Network Architecture</strong>:</p>
        <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">
            <li><strong>Host Network</strong>: 192.168.x.x (where production MySQL lives at 192.168.1.198:3306)</li>
            <li><strong>Docker Network</strong>: 172.20.0.0/16 bridge (where containers live at 172.20.0.2, etc.)</li>
            <li><strong>Container DNS Resolution</strong>: Resolves "database" to 172.20.0.3 (local Docker service), NOT to external hosts</li>
            <li><strong>Firewall/Routing</strong>: Docker daemon does not expose host network routes to containers by default</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>Why Port 3001 Works</strong>: The native Perl process via `perl script/comserv_server.pl -p3001` runs directly on the host OS. It can access the host network and reach 192.168.1.198 because it's not isolated like Docker containers.</p>
    </div>

    <h4 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Configuration Mismatch</h4>
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
        <tr style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Component</strong></th>
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Configured For</strong></th>
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Actually Using</strong></th>
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Status</strong></th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">docker-compose.yml</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Production MySQL at 192.168.1.198</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Hardcoded credentials (SECURITY RISK)</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: #d32f2f;">❌ EXPOSED</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Running Docker env vars</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">COMSERV_DB_LOCAL_ENCY_HOST=192.168.1.198</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">database (localhost via Docker DNS)</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: #4caf50;">✅ OVERRIDE</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">db_config.json (mounted)</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Production 192.168.1.198 + ZeroTier IPs</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Not used (env vars take priority)</td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: #ff9800;">⚠️ IGNORED</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h4 style="color: #d32f2f; font-family: var(--header-font);">What Changed to Get Ports 3000/5000 Returning Content</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
        <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>Key Commit</strong>: <code>03b76bd5</code> - "Update Docker development setup and enhance Kubernetes migration documentation"</p>
        <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>Change</strong>: docker-compose.yml was modified to:</p>
        <ol style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">
            <li>Mount code volumes (lib/, script/, root/, config/, t/)</li>
            <li>Configure Starman servers via Supervisor in containers</li>
            <li>Set healthcheck endpoints to verify port responsiveness</li>
            <li>Configure Redis and local config-db services</li>
        </ol>
        <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>Result</strong>: Containers now start successfully and respond to HTTP requests on ports 3000/5000, but the application cannot access the production MySQL database because of network isolation.</p>
    </div>

    <h4 style="color: #d32f2f; font-family: var(--header-font);">Why Docker Still Can't Connect to Production MySQL</h4>
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
        <tr style="background-color: var(--light-color);">
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Factor</strong></th>
            <th style="text-align: left; padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Details</strong></th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Network Isolation</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Docker bridge network (172.20.0.0/16) does not include routes to host network (192.168.0.0/16). Container routing table only knows about Docker internal addresses.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>DNS Resolution</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Docker-internal DNS (127.0.0.11:53) resolves all hostnames to Docker services only. External hosts like 192.168.1.198 are not resolvable unless Docker daemon has host network access configured.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>Firewall Rules</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Even if routing existed, Linux iptables rules may block traffic. Docker's default FORWARD chain policies restrict inter-network communication.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr style="background-color: #f9f9f9;">
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);"><strong>MySQL Service Binding</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); color: var(--text-color);">Production MySQL at 192.168.1.198 may only be listening on eth0 (host network interface). It doesn't know about the Docker bridge network, so it cannot route return traffic.</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h4 style="color: #4caf50; font-family: var(--header-font); margin-top: var(--spacing-large);">Solutions (In Priority Order)</h4>
    <div style="background-color: #e8f5e9; border: 1px solid #4caf50; padding: var(--spacing-medium); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
        <ol style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); line-height: 1.8;">
            <li><strong>Short-term (Immediate - 30 min)</strong>: Use <code>--network host</code> for development
                <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 5px;">
                    <li>Add <code>network_mode: host</code> to web-dev service in docker-compose.yml</li>
                    <li>Container shares host network stack, can directly access 192.168.1.198</li>
                    <li>Trade-off: Loses network isolation, less secure but works immediately</li>
                    <li>Example: <code>curl -I http://localhost:3000</code> still works (port 3000 is published on host:3000)</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Mid-term (Development - 2-3 hours)</strong>: Add custom bridge network routing
                <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 5px;">
                    <li>Create docker network with host route: <code>docker network create --driver bridge --subnet 172.20.0.0/16 --gateway 172.20.0.1 comserv-bridge</code></li>
                    <li>Add route from Docker to host network: <code>docker run --cap-add NET_ADMIN ... route add -net 192.168.0.0/16 gw 172.17.0.1</code></li>
                    <li>Or use macvlan driver to give containers direct access to host network interface</li>
                    <li>Requires elevated privileges and more complex networking config</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li style="margin-top: 10px;"><strong>Best-practice (Long-term Production - 4-6 hours)</strong>: Use Zerotier or Tailscale
                <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); margin-top: 5px;">
                    <li>Install Zerotier or Tailscale client in Docker containers (add to Dockerfile)</li>
                    <li>Database server joins same Zerotier/Tailscale network (already joined)</li>
                    <li>Containers resolve database via virtual IP (e.g., 10.147.1.100 or 100.64.x.x)</li>
                    <li>Works for local, on-site, and off-site scenarios without exposing host network</li>
                    <li>More secure than host networking, enables future multi-cloud deployments</li>
                    <li>Recommended for Kubernetes Phase 6-7</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-100">
        <h2 id="overview" style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Overview</h2>
        <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">This document serves as a living blueprint for transitioning Comserv from manual server deployments to a fully containerized, Kubernetes-based infrastructure. The strategy spans 7 implementation phases over 4-6 months, with clear deliverables, pros/cons analysis, and decision points at each phase.</p>
        <p style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);"><strong>Current Deployment Model</strong>: Manual SSH + git pull + restart starman on production server. <strong>Target Model</strong>: Zero-downtime, auto-scaling Kubernetes cluster with CI/CD automation.</p>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-100">
        <h2 id="current-state" style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Current State Analysis</h2>

        <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); font-size: var(--font-size-large);">Existing Deployment Workflow</h3>
        <div style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
            <pre style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: monospace; margin: 0;"><code>Developer Machines (Multiple)
↓ [git clone + local changes]GitHub Repository
    ↓ [git push from developer machine]
Production Server (On-Premises)
    ↓ [Manual: git pull + comserv_server.pl + restart starman]
Live Application
                </code></pre>
            </div>        <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); font-size: var(--font-size-large);">Current Pain Points</h3>
        <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">
            <li><strong>Manual updates</strong>: Each deployment requires SSH access and manual steps</li>
            <li><strong>Environment inconsistency</strong>: Developer machine ≠ production server setup</li>
            <li><strong>No rollback mechanism</strong>: Failed updates require manual recovery</li>
            <li><strong>Scaling limitation</strong>: Adding servers means duplicating manual setup</li>
            <li><strong>Update downtime</strong>: Application down during comserv_server.pl execution</li>
            <li><strong>Port mapping issues</strong>: As discovered with Docker testing (port 5000/3000 confusion)</li>
            <li><strong>Database management</strong>: Manual synchronization across environments</li>
            <li><strong>Developer onboarding</strong>: New developers must set up entire Perl/MySQL stack locally</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); font-size: var(--font-size-large);">Current Infrastructure</h3>
        <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">
            <li><strong>Deployment Target</strong>: On-premises Proxmox with potential for additional physical servers</li>
            <li><strong>Application Runtime</strong>: Catalyst Perl framework via Starman server</li>
            <li><strong>Database</strong>: MySQL/PostgreSQL with future SQLite offline mode option</li>
            <li><strong>Version Control</strong>: Local git clone, manual push/pull workflow (only one developer currently)</li>
            <li><strong>CI/CD</strong>: None (manual everything)</li>
            <li><strong>Container Status</strong>: Docker container exists but not yet integrated with production workflow</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-100">
        <h2 id="target-state" style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Target State Vision</h2>

        <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); font-size: var(--font-size-large);">End Goal: Production-Ready Kubernetes</h3>
        <div style="background-color: var(--light-color); padding: var(--spacing-medium); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); margin: var(--spacing-small) 0;">
            <pre style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: monospace; margin: 0;"><code>Developer Machines → Standardized Docker Dev Environment
↓GitHub Repository → Automated via CI/CD
    ↓
CI/CD Pipeline (GitHub Actions) → Build, Test, Push to Registry
    ↓
Kubernetes Cluster (Multi-node on Proxmox)
    ├─ App Containers (Replicated, Auto-scaled)
    ├─ Database Service (Persistent)
    └─ Monitoring/Logging
    ↓
Live Application (Zero-Downtime Deployments)
                </code></pre>
            </div>        <h3 style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); font-size: var(--font-size-large);">Key Benefits When Achieved</h3>
        <ul style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font);">
            <li> <strong>Zero-downtime updates</strong> - Blue-green or rolling updates</li>
            <li> <strong>Automatic scaling</strong> - Handle load spikes automatically</li>
            <li> <strong>Consistency</strong> - Same environment from dev → prod</li>
            <li> <strong>Rollback capability</strong> - Revert to previous version instantly</li>
            <li> <strong>Multi-developer friendly</strong> - Standardized local environment</li>
            <li> <strong>Future cloud migration</strong> - K8s on Proxmox → Cloud K8s seamlessly</li>
            <li> <strong>Self-healing infrastructure</strong> - Failed containers restart automatically</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-100">
        <h2 id="phases" style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font);">Migration Phases Overview</h2>

        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: var(--spacing-medium) 0;">
            <tr>
                <th style="background-color: var(--table-header-bg); color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);">Phase</th>
                <th style="background-color: var(--table-header-bg); color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);">Name</th>
                <th style="background-color: var(--table-header-bg); color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);">Duration</th>
                <th style="background-color: var(--table-header-bg); color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--header-font); padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);">Environment(s)</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td style="color: var(--text-color); font-family: var(--body-font); padding: var(--spacing-small); border: 1px solid var(--border-color);"><strong>0</strong></td>
